`%notin%` <- Negate(`%in%`)

recur_factorial <- function(n) {
if(n <= 1) {
return(1)
} else { 
return(n * recur_factorial(n-1))
}
}

The purpose of this script is to investigate differences between male and female bearing pregnancies (placenta)

Lets talk about sex baby!

Import Counts and Sample Data

  • This step imports the raw placenta counts data and the sample data
  • PAC0071 and PAC0131 removed due to low reads
  • PAC0041, PAC0039, PAC0045, PAC0008, PAC0035, PAC0024, PAC0034, PAC0006 removed due to decidual contamination
  • The counts have not been normalised or filtered for low expression
  • These are raw counts and not cpm (or similar)
# import raw miRNA counts table
countsPlacenta <- read.table(here("rawData", "counts_placenta.tsv"), 
                             sep = "\t", 
                             header = TRUE, 
                             row.names = "mirna")


# remove the "_merge_R1" from the sample name for simplification
names(countsPlacenta) <- sub("_merge_R1","",names(countsPlacenta))

# remove the "Q" prefix from the sample names so I can replace with PAC
names(countsPlacenta) <- sub("Q","",names(countsPlacenta))

# Create a df of sample names from the counts table, then add PAC prefix and pad to 7 characters
countsPlacentaNames <- data.frame(names(countsPlacenta)) %>%
  mutate(names.countsPlacenta. = paste0("PAC",stringr::str_pad(names.countsPlacenta., width = 4, pad = "0")))

# convert back to a vector so I can overwrite the colnames in the counts table
countsPlacentaNames <- countsPlacentaNames[,]

# replace the old sample names with the new names (PACXXXX)
names(countsPlacenta) <- countsPlacentaNames

# ensure the columns are ordered by assending sample name
countsPlacenta <- countsPlacenta[,order(colnames(countsPlacenta),decreasing=FALSE)]

countsPlacenta_noHV <- countsPlacenta %>%
  # remove poorly sequenced samples
  dplyr::select(., -c(PAC0071,PAC0131)) %>% 
  # remove samples failing tests for purity
  dplyr::select(., -c(PAC0041, PAC0039, PAC0045, PAC0008, PAC0035, PAC0024, PAC0034, PAC0006))

samples_noHV <- readRDS(here("cleanData", "samples_noHV.rds")) %>%
  dplyr::filter(., !grepl('PAC0131', samplename))  %>% # remove PAC0131 - low reads
  dplyr::filter(., !grepl('PAC0071', samplename)) # remove PAC0071 - low reads

samples <- readRDS(here("cleanData/samples.rds"))

Filter sequencing noise

  • Here any individual observation with less than five counts is considered to be sequencing noise and is reduced to zero and removed by filtering.
  • Counts less than 5 reduced to 0
  • Logic check and record how many miRs will be filtered
  • Filter to remove miRs with zero counts in all samples
# remove multimapped miRNA with identical mature sequences
identicalMature <- c("hsa-miR-199b-3p", "hsa-miR-365b-3p", "hsa-miR-517b-3p", "hsa-miR-518d-5p", "hsa-miR-520c-5p", "hsa-miR-526a", "hsa-miR-518e-5p", "hsa-miR-519b-5p", "hsa-miR-522-5p", "hsa-miR-523-5p", "hsa-miR-519c-5p")

# here the mature miRNA with the lowest number is retained
countsPlacenta_noHV <- countsPlacenta_noHV %>%
  subset(., rownames(countsPlacenta_noHV) %notin% identicalMature)

# reduce any individual count less than five to zero
countsPlacenta_noHV[countsPlacenta_noHV < 5] <- 0

# check to establish if any miRNA have no expression across all samples
table(rowSums(countsPlacenta_noHV == 0) == 86)
## 
## FALSE  TRUE 
##  1420   610
# remove miRNAs with zero counts in all samples
countsPlacenta_noHV <- countsPlacenta_noHV[ rowSums(countsPlacenta_noHV)!=0, ]

After filtering out the sequencing noise (sequence counts with low confidence) we are left with 1420 unique miRNAs. Of the initial miRs, 621 had initial raw counts between 1:4 (inc) and have now been filtered.

Establish DGEList object

The counts and samples data can now be combined into a single list object for use in differential expression analysis downstream.

# new df of miRNA names for DGEList object
genes <- as.character(rownames(countsPlacenta_noHV)) %>%
  as.data.frame() %>%
  set_colnames("SYMBOL") 

# new DGEList object for differential expression analysis
DGEList_placenta_noHV <- DGEList(counts=countsPlacenta_noHV, 
                                 samples=samples_noHV, 
                                 genes = genes)

Plot the distribution of miRs before normalisation

TMM normalisation of libraries

Before differential expression analysis the sample libraries need to be normalised to account for differences in initial library size.
Normalising the libraries allows for the direct comparison between samples.
Here the Trimmed Mean of M Values method is used.
Prior to normalisation the placenta libraries are within a similar range with and centered around 0-1 CPM (log2)

Filter biological noise and plot

Once the libraries are normalised we can filter for biological noise - i.e. miRNAs that are present in such small numbers that they are not biologically relevant. Here a count of greater than 1.05 CPM in 22 or more samples is considered biologically relevant for this analysis. A count of 2 CPM is the equivalant of ~12 transcripts in the smallest library. The number of samples (here 29) is chosen such that it is possible for a miRNA to be expressed in every sample of the smallest group (here hypoxic).

# calculate the cpm value of a read count of 10 given the mean library size (to be used in the keep.genes)
cpm(10, mean(DGEList_placenta_noHV$samples$lib.size))
##          [,1]
## [1,] 1.195957
# returns a value of 1.05689

# new df of unfiltered cpm for the reduced DGEList
rawCpm_placenta_noHV <- cpm(DGEList_placenta_noHV)

# new df of unfiltered log 2 cpm for the reduced DGEList
rawlcpm_placenta_noHV <- cpm(DGEList_placenta_noHV, log = TRUE)

# remove low expressed genes (22 hypoxic = smaller group)
keep.exprs_noHV <- rowSums(rawCpm_placenta_noHV > 2.5) >= 29
DGEList_placenta_noHV <- DGEList_placenta_noHV[keep.exprs_noHV,, keep.lib.sizes = FALSE]

MDS Plots

The multidimensional scaling plots create a temp. log fold change between pairs.
Here we see that the Leading logFC on dimension 1 seperates the samples by batch indicating the need for batch correction.

par(mfrow=c(1,1))

Sex Independent Differential Expression Analysis - Oxygen (no dijoxin):

  • Option 1: Factorial formula and no contrast A nested factorial model allows you to compare groups within each sex. This achieves the aim of treating the two sexes separately:
# design to test DE between T1 and T2 looking at female and male baring pregnancies seperately
design_independent_oxygenation <- model.matrix(~ updatedFetalSex + 
                                                 updatedFetalSex:oxygenation + 
                                                 processGroup, 
                                               data = samples_noHV)

voom_independent_oxygenation <- voomWithQualityWeights(DGEList_placenta_noHV, 
                                                       design_independent_oxygenation, plot=TRUE)

fit_independent_oxygenation <- lmFit(voom_independent_oxygenation, 
                                     design_independent_oxygenation)
fit_independent_oxygenation <- eBayes(fit_independent_oxygenation)
summary(decideTests(fit_independent_oxygenation)) # before FDR correction
##        (Intercept) updatedFetalSexXY processGroupgroupB
## Down            11                32                286
## NotSig          18               567                 76
## Up             608                38                275
##        updatedFetalSexXX:oxygenationoxygenated
## Down                                       113
## NotSig                                     369
## Up                                         155
##        updatedFetalSexXY:oxygenationoxygenated
## Down                                       150
## NotSig                                     302
## Up                                         185

Female Tests - Pre versus Post maternal blood flow

topTable_female_oxygenation <- topTable(fit_independent_oxygenation, 
                                        coef = 4, 
                                        n = Inf, 
                                        sort = "p", 
                                        p = 0.05, 
                                        adjust.method = "fdr") # trimester 2 vs trimester 1 for females

AllTable_female_oxygenation <- topTable(fit_independent_oxygenation, 
                                        coef = 4, 
                                        n = Inf, 
                                        sort = "p")

Volcano plot - Oxygen (Female)

  • There are 73 down-regulated, 127 up-regulated miRs in post oxygen group, with 550 miRs not significantly different between pre and post oxygen.
  • Of the 73 down-regulated miRs, 30 have a logFC <= -1, and of the 127 up-regulated miRs, 50 have a logFC >= 1.

Scatter plot of logFC for the regresion model <=10 v > 10 indepedent for each fetal sex (control for sequencing batch)

logFC_plot <- AllTable_female_oxygenation %>%
  full_join(., AllTable_male_oxygenation, by = "SYMBOL") %>%
  dplyr::select(., SYMBOL, logFC_female = logFC.x, logFC_male = logFC.y, AveExpr.x)

# adds logical test to assign a colour to each quadrant of the scatter plot
logFC_plot$colour <- ifelse(
                            logFC_plot$logFC_female < 0 & logFC_plot$logFC_male < 0, "#D55E00", # orange
                      ifelse(
                            logFC_plot$logFC_female > 0 & logFC_plot$logFC_male > 0, "#009E73", # green
                      ifelse(
                            logFC_plot$logFC_female < 0 & logFC_plot$logFC_male > 0, "#CC79A7", # kinda purple
                      ifelse(
                            logFC_plot$logFC_female > 0 & logFC_plot$logFC_male < 0, "#0072B2", NA)))) # blue

# Scatter plot of the logFC for the with and without dijoxin regression models
ggplot(data = logFC_plot, aes(x = logFC_female, y = logFC_male)) +
  geom_point(colour = logFC_plot$colour, size = 5) +
  # ggtitle("Scatter plot of logFC: regression models DE T1:T2 male and female") +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype = "dotted") +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 0, linetype = "dotted") +
  # geom_text(x = 2, y = 2, label = "logFC +ve in both models") +
  # geom_text(x = -2, y = -2, label = "logFC -ve in both models") +
  # geom_text(x = 2, y = -2, label = "logFC +ve in female -ve in male") +
  # geom_text(x = -2, y = 2, label = "logFC -ve in female +ve in male") +
  # theme_light() +
  theme(text = element_text(size = 25, colour = "black"),
        axis.text = element_text(size = 25, colour = "black")) +
  theme(legend.position = "none") + # take out the legend for the poster
